    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3299207842" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3299207842" />
    <a title="ALLEN" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58158333-allen"><img alt="ALLEN" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578421145p2/58158333.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3299207842?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="ALLEN" class="user" itemprop="url" name="ALLEN" href="/user/show/58158333-allen">ALLEN</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3299207842" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8024141581370055444">Probably Tennessee Williams’ three greatest plays are <i>The Glass Menagerie</i> (1944), <i>A Streetcar Named Desire</i> (1951), and <i>Cat on a Hot Tin Roof</i> (1955), and in all of them the male figures are problematic. In <i>Menagerie</i>, the Depression-era father simply deserted his family; in <i>Streetcar</i> the male and female leads are strongly sexualized polar opposites (“the stud and the queen” said critic Ethan Mordden); and in this play, <i>Cat</i>, family patriarch “Big Daddy” Pollitt faces his last day on earth without h</span>
  <span id="freeText8024141581370055444" style="display:none">Probably Tennessee Williams’ three greatest plays are <i>The Glass Menagerie</i> (1944), <i>A Streetcar Named Desire</i> (1951), and <i>Cat on a Hot Tin Roof</i> (1955), and in all of them the male figures are problematic. In <i>Menagerie</i>, the Depression-era father simply deserted his family; in <i>Streetcar</i> the male and female leads are strongly sexualized polar opposites (“the stud and the queen” said critic Ethan Mordden); and in this play, <i>Cat</i>, family patriarch “Big Daddy” Pollitt faces his last day on earth without having made sense of his own life or mortality. What’s worse, he despises the older, responsible son Gooper, and the son he loves, golden boy Brick, seems well on the way to becoming a career alcoholic, behavior that baffles all involved, especially his wife Maggie. When this play opens, the older son and his wife are in full-bore conspiracy to inherit “28,000 acres of the richest land this side of the valley Nile” from Big Daddy. Brick’s chances are not good, but our sympathies are with Maggie if for no other reason than she’s much less venal than Gooper and his wife. <br /><br />Along the way we are treated to three acts of drama, including a thunderstorm, family retainers, an unctuous clergyman, long-suffering “Big Mama,” an unresolved sexual scandal, and a passel of Gooper’s bratty children Maggie unceremoniously tags “no-neck monsters.” There is just enough humor to keep the show moving swiftly, but nothing to descend to the level of stereotype, though at times it comes close. What this masterpiece must have -- on the stage or the screen or in our minds -- are for such strong and convincing characters to be played strongly. <br /><br />A note on the text: the original 1955 production starred Barbara Bel Geddes in the title role, followed in 1958 by the sultry but bowdlerized M-G-M movie starring Elizabeth Taylor. This version from 1974 uses a different third act, Williams’ favorite, and it starred the radiant Elizabeth Ashley. It is also a good deal less tame on matters of sexuality than earlier versions and well worth reading -- or watching. By the end of the play, is there hope for Brick and Maggie? I won’t spoil the ending.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8024141581370055444" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


