        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2156465289" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3193875977104789332"><i>“I&apos;ve got the guts to die. What I want to know is, have you got the guts to live?” </i><br/><br/>This play was required reading for my literature course at school and I&apos;ve got to say that I loved this SO much more than I was expecting to... <br/><br/>Sometimes I really struggle reading plays, as I tend to feel a real disconnect from each of the characters, but Tennessee Williams writes so brilliantly that I became attached to multiple characters within the confines of a mere 100 pages. The character of Brick especially</span>
  <span id="freeText3193875977104789332" style="display:none"><i>“I've got the guts to die. What I want to know is, have you got the guts to live?” </i><br /><br />This play was required reading for my literature course at school and I've got to say that I loved this SO much more than I was expecting to... <br /><br />Sometimes I really struggle reading plays, as I tend to feel a real disconnect from each of the characters, but Tennessee Williams writes so brilliantly that I became attached to multiple characters within the confines of a mere 100 pages. The character of Brick especially, in my personal opinion, was fleshed out so well both in the dialogue which he spoke, and in the square-bracketed text of the play. And some of the dialogue was so sad! If I had been reading this at my own leisure, I probably would have cried. <br /><br />So many topics and issues were discussed within such as short amount of time and it made for a really exciting story! If you haven't read any of Tennessee Williams' work, I think starting here would be a great place to start (but don't hold my word to it since I have yet to pick up more of his work)!</span>
  <a data-text-id="3193875977104789332" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


